  <h2>Child & Household Survey Data: Early Childhood, Household Context & Insights Dashboard</h2>
  <p><strong>ğŸ“‚ Datasets:</strong><br>
    <a href="https://github.com/SIAnalyticsLab/30daychallengeguide/blob/main/child_data_day_07.csv">child_data_day_07.csv</a> â€” Early childhood survey day-07<br>
    <a href="https://github.com/SIAnalyticsLab/30daychallengeguide/blob/main/child_data_day_21.csv">child_data_day_21.csv</a> â€” Early childhood survey day-21 follow-up<br>
    <a href="https://github.com/SIAnalyticsLab/30daychallengeguide/blob/main/household_data.csv">household_data.csv</a> â€” Household-level context data</p>

  <hr>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>ğŸ§© Background</h2>
    <p>
      Todayâ€™s task invites you to integrate **child survey data** at two time-points (Day 07 and Day 21) with **household context information**.  
      These datasets capture early childhood indicators (nutritional, developmental, feeding practices) and household characteristics (socio-economic status, utilities, family composition), enabling a rich analysis of how household context influences child outcomes.
    </p>
    <p>
      With these combined sources you can ask:
      ğŸ’¡ How do child development indicators evolve from Day 07 to Day 21?  
      ğŸ’¡ How does household context (e.g., income level, utilities access, family size) influence those changes?  
      ğŸ’¡ Which children or households show unexpected trends â€” e.g., improvement despite constraints or vice-versa?
    </p>
    <p><strong>ğŸ“„ Dataset Overview:</strong></p>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Variable</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>child_id</td><td>Unique identifier for each child</td></tr>
      <tr><td>day</td><td>Time-point (07 or 21)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>nutritional_score</td><td>Composite indicator of nutrition status</td></tr>
      <tr><td>development_score</td><td>Composite indicator of developmental milestones</td></tr>
      <tr><td>feeding_practice</td><td>Type of feeding practice reported</td></tr>
      <tr><td>household_id</td><td>Identifier linking to household data</td></tr>
      <tr><td>household_income</td><td>Household monthly income</td></tr>
      <tr><td>utilities_access</td><td>Binary indicator: access to utilities (Yes/No)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>family_size</td><td>Number of individuals in the household</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p><strong>ğŸ’¡ Note:</strong> These are anonymized household and child-level records intended for analytical practice and visualization.</p>
  </div>

  <hr>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>ğŸ¯ Daily Task Objective</h2>
    <p>Create a <strong>Child & Household Insights Dashboard</strong> that answers:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>ğŸ‘¶ How do nutritional and developmental scores change between Day 07 and Day 21?</li>
      <li>ğŸ  Which household characteristics (income level, utilities, family size) are associated with greater improvements?</li>
      <li>ğŸ“Š Which children or households demonstrate unexpected trajectories â€” e.g., low income but high improvement?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Your challenge is to merge the child survey data at two time-points with the household dataset, clean and calculate derived metrics, and create visuals that highlight dynamics, drivers, and outcomes.</p>
  </div>

  <hr>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>ğŸ§® Step-by-Step Instructions</h2>

    <h3>1ï¸âƒ£ Load and Explore the Datasets</h3>
    <p>
      â€¢ R: <code>readr::read_csv("child_data_day_07.csv")</code>, <code>readr::read_csv("child_data_day_21.csv")</code>, <code>readr::read_csv("household_data.csv")</code><br>
      â€¢ Python: <code>pd.read_csv("child_data_day_07.csv")</code>, <code>pd.read_csv("child_data_day_21.csv")</code>, <code>pd.read_csv("household_data.csv")</code><br>
      â€¢ Power BI: Home â†’ Get Data â†’ Web/CSV â†’ paste each GitHub raw link.
    </p>
    <p>Inspect each dataset for consistent IDs, missing values, and data types. Confirm that <code>household_id</code> links properly between child and household files.</p>

    <h3>2ï¸âƒ£ Clean and Prepare</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Convert numeric fields (<code>nutritional_score</code>, <code>development_score</code>, <code>household_income</code>) to numeric types.</li>
      <li>Create a combined table:
        <ul>
          <li>Merge Day 07 & Day 21 child data on <code>child_id</code>.</li>
          <li>Compute <strong>Score Change = development_score_Day21 â€“ development_score_Day07</strong>.</li>
          <li>Join household_data by <code>household_id</code>.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Create derived fields such as:
        <ul>
          <li>ğŸ“ˆ Improvement Rate = (Score Change Ã· development_score_Day07) Ã— 100</li>
          <li>ğŸ  High SES Flag = (household_income > median income)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3ï¸âƒ£ Build Your Dashboard</h3>
    <p>Using R (ggplot2/plotly/quarto), Python (matplotlib/plotly/dash), or Power BI, consider visuals such as:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>ğŸ”„ Bar Chart: Average Improvement Rate by SES group (High vs Low)</li>
      <li>ğŸ“Š Scatter Plot: Household Income vs Improvement Rate (bubble size = family_size)</li>
      <li>ğŸ—ºï¸ Map or Heat Table: Improvement Rate by region or utilities access (if region field exists)</li>
      <li>ğŸ“ˆ Line Chart: Nutritional vs Developmental Score change over time</li>
      <li>ğŸ’¬ KPI Cards: Average Score Change, % of children with >10% improvement, Median household income</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>ğŸ’¡ Power BI Tip:</strong> Use slicers for utilities_access and family_size category. Use bookmarks to compare Day 07 vs Day 21 results.<br>
    <strong>ğŸ’¡ R/Python Tip:</strong> Use interactive filters or dashboards to let users explore by household income bracket or utilities access.</p>

    <h3>4ï¸âƒ£ Add Key Metrics / KPI Cards</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>ğŸ“Š Average Development Score Change</li>
      <li>ğŸ‘¥ % Children with Positive Improvement (>0)</li>
      <li>ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ‘©â€ğŸ‘§â€ğŸ‘¦ Median Household Income</li>
      <li>ğŸ  % Households with Utilities Access</li>
      <li>ğŸ“‰ Average Improvement Rate in Low-Income Households</li>
    </ul>
